<h3 class=3D"SubHeading">How the Calculator Works</h3>
<div class=3D"PageInfo">
<ol>
<li>Choose the major diagonal length and minor diagonal length of the kite:=
 you can choose a whole number, decimal or fraction.
<ul>
<li>You can type a fraction by typing the numerator then '/' then the denom=
inator.</li>
<li>You can type a mixed number by typing the whole-number part, then a spa=
ce then the fraction part.</li>
<li class=3D"IBlue">Examples: 2 1/2 (two and one-half); 3 4/5 (three and fo=
ur-fifths); 7 1/3 (seven and one-third).</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Choose your units of measurement (default is none)</li>
<li>Choose your desired accuracy (default is 2 decimal places)</li>
<li>Click the Find Area button</li>
<li>You will be shown the area as a decimal (and also a fraction if you typ=
ed the length as a fraction).</li>
</ol>
</div><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_3_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-s=
ticky-container adthrive-content adthrive-content-3"></div>
<h3 class=3D"SubHeading"><a id=3D"Formula">Area of a Kite Formula</a></h3>
<div class=3D"PageInfo">
<p class=3D"center-align">
<img alt=3D"area of a kite formula image" class=3D"ss-lazy" data-src=3D"htt=
ps://www.math-salamanders.com/image-files/area-of-a-kite-dart-formula-image=
.gif" height=3D"189" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKA=
AEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" title=3D"area of a kite formula image" wid=
th=3D"454">
</p>
<div class=3D"WhiteBG center-align">
<p class=3D"BoldCt">The formula for the area of a kite or a dart (which is =
a concave kite) is:
<mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" display=
=3D"true" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"0" style=3D"font-size: 119.5%;=
 position: relative;"><mjx-math display=3D"true" class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hid=
den=3D"true" style=3D"margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px;"><mjx-mi class=
=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D434 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mo class=
=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c3D"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-texat=
om space=3D"4" texclass=3D"ORD"><mjx-mfrac><mjx-frac type=3D"d"><mjx-num><m=
jx-nstrut type=3D"d"></mjx-nstrut><mjx-mn class=3D"mjx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"m=
jx-c31"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-num><mjx-dbox><mjx-dtable><mjx-line type=3D"=
d"></mjx-line><mjx-row><mjx-den><mjx-dstrut type=3D"d"></mjx-dstrut><mjx-mn=
 class=3D"mjx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c32"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-den></mjx-=
row></mjx-dtable></mjx-dbox></mjx-frac></mjx-mfrac></mjx-texatom><mjx-mi cl=
ass=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D44E TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi cl=
ass=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D44F TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mstyl=
e><mjx-mspace style=3D"width: 0.278em;"></mjx-mspace></mjx-mstyle></mjx-mat=
h><mjx-assistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"block"><math xmlns=3D"h=
ttp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"block"><mi>A</mi><mo>=3D</mo>=
<mrow data-mjx-texclass=3D"ORD"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow><=
mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mstyle scriptlevel=3D"0"><mspace width=3D"0.278em"></ms=
pace></mstyle></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container>
</p>
<p>where <span class=3D"Bold">A</span> is the area of the kite, <span class=
=3D"Bold">a</span> is the major diagonal length and <span class=3D"Bold">b<=
/span> is the minor diagonal length of the kite</p>
</div>
</div><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_4_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-s=
ticky-container adthrive-content adthrive-content-4"></div>
<h3 class=3D"SubHeading"><a id=3D"Explanation">Area of a Kite Explanation</=
a></h3>
<div class=3D"PageInfo">
<p>First let's look at the kite below.</p>
<p class=3D"center-align">
<img alt=3D"area of a kite labelled image" class=3D"ss-lazy ImageBd" data-s=
rc=3D"https://www.math-salamanders.com/image-files/area-of-a-kite-labelled.=
gif" height=3D"125" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAA=
EALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" title=3D"area of a kite labelled image" wid=
th=3D"198">
</p>
<p>Now we are going to cut the kite in half along the major diagonal.</p>
<p class=3D"ImageCt">
<img alt=3D"area of a kite formula 1 image" class=3D"ss-lazy" data-src=3D"h=
ttps://www.math-salamanders.com/image-files/area-of-a-kite-formula-1.gif" h=
eight=3D"126" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAA=
AAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" title=3D"area of a kite formula 1 image" width=3D=
"337">
</p>
<p>Next we are going to put the half-kite inside a blue rectangle..</p>
<p class=3D"ImageCt">
<img alt=3D"area of a kite formula 2 image" class=3D"ss-lazy" data-src=3D"h=
ttps://www.math-salamanders.com/image-files/area-of-a-kite-formula-2.gif" h=
eight=3D"125" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAA=
AAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" title=3D"area of a kite formula 2 image" width=3D=
"340">
</p>
<p>You can see the half-kite forms a triangle which takes up exactly half o=
f the area of the blue rectangle it is inside.</p>
<p>So the full size kite, which has twice the area of the half-size kite, w=
ill take up the whole area of the blue rectangle which the half-size kite i=
s inside.</p>
<p class=3D"Bold">So the area of the blue rectangle and the area of the who=
le kite are equal.</p>
<p>The blue rectangle has the length of the major diagonal (a) and the widt=
h of half of the minor diagonal (=C2=BD b).</p>
<p>To find the area of the blue rectangle, we multiply the adjacent sides t=
ogether which gives us:</p>
<p>
